    "37887905": {
      "title": "Reduced transport of methionine in intestines of chickens infected with Eimeria necatrix",
      "abstract": "The in vitro uptake of L-methionine in the jejunum of chickens inoculated with 50,000 oocysts of Eimeria necatrix was less than the uptake measured in uninoculated birds at days 6, 13, and 21 postinoculation (PI). Less methionine was taken up in the ileum of inoculated birds than in uninoculated birds on days 6 and 13 PI. Infection did not affect methionine absorption by the duodenum on days 2, 6, 13, or 21 PI or by the jejunum and ileum on day 2 PI. Studies on the kinetics of transport showed that infection reduced both the diffusion and mediated components of methionine transport in the jejunum at day 7 PI. Experiments using ligated intestinal loops in vivo confirmed the reduction of methionine absorption in the jejunum of infected birds. The kinetics and specificity of amino acid absorption in the intestine of chickens have been reviewed (Lerner, 1971). No complete studies on the effects of coccidia on these same parameters are available although Turk and Stephens (1969b) and Turk (1970) reported results of preliminary experiments. Coccidiosis can affect the overall absorption of substrates such as zinc (Turk and Steuphens, 1966, 1967a, b, 1969a, 1970a, b), oleic acid (Turk and Stephens, 1967b, c, 1969a, 1970b), calcium (Turk, 1973), and glucose (Giese et al., 1971), as measured by the appearance of radioactivity in the blood and/or tissues of infected birds after oral administration of labeled substrate. Changes have also been reported in the digestion and absorption of protein in chickens infected with coccidia (Turk and Stephens, 1969b; Turk, 1970, 1972). The present study examined the effects of Eimeria necatrix on the uptake of L-methionine in vivo and in vitro to determine: (1) changes in absorption at various days postinoculation (PI); (2) the specific kinetic parameters affected (i.e., changes in the mediated and/or diffusion components of transport); and (3) the specific areas of the intestine affected. MATERIALS AND METHODS"
    }
